article.headline: Martin's line: 21 points, 12 boards
article.story:
EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- Kenyon Martin and the New Jersey Nets finally won consecutive home games for the first time this season, withstanding another big comeback by the Phoenix Suns. Martin had 21 points and 12 rebounds on the court where the defending Eastern Conference champions were nearly invincible the past two seasons, leading New Jersey to a 99-88 victory Saturday night. The consecutive wins improved the Nets home record to 4-6 "This will hopefully get us going on the right track," Martin said. "We stuck in there tonight and we didn't fall apart like we have in the past." Richard Jefferson had 18 points and 11 rebounds for the Nets, who had six players in double figures. Jason Kidd had 17, Jason Collins and Aaron Williams scored 13 each and Lucious Harris 10. The Nets played before a sparse crowd for a second straight night because of a snowstorm. The attendance was announced as 14,639, but the actual turnout was closer to 5,000. Shawn Marion paced the Suns with 25 points and 17 rebounds. Stephon Marbury had 23 and Jake Voskuhl added 14 before fouling out. The Suns played without Amare Stoudemire, who sprained his left ankle Friday night in Boston and will miss the remainder of Phoenix's road trip. The Suns, who overcame a 29-point deficit to beat the Celtics on Friday night, scored the first 14 points of the fourth quarter to pull within one. Phoenix took its final lead when Marbury hit a jump shot with 4:36 remaining to make it 86-85. The Nets, who missed their first 10 shots of the fourth quarter, finally got a basket from Martin on a hook shot to reclaim the lead. They scored the next six to put the game away. The Nets shot a season-high 48.7 percent from the field. "Everybody came to work tonight," Kidd said. "Nobody panicked. We settled down, made some stops, got some baskets and free throws." The Suns lamented their inability to sustain the fourth quarter run. "It was there for us to take and didn't have enough juice in the end," Suns coach Frank Johnson said. "We took the lead on Marbury's runner and then, all of a sudden, we stopped when they went into a zone." The Nets led 54-48 after closing out the first half with a 7-0 run. Kidd hit a 3-pointer to trigger the run and fed Williams for two field goals. New Jersey appeared to break the game open in the third, running off 11 straight points for 78-64 lead. Harris ignited the surge with a trio of jumpers, including a 3-pointer, and finished the quarter with 10 points as the Nets led 81-66.

Game notes
The Suns were among the lucky air travelers during the snowstorm. While thousands were stranded at airports, the Suns flew by charter from Boston to Newark following their game Friday night. The Suns skipped their morning shootaround and held a team meeting at the hotel in their only concession to the elements. The Suns hoped their travel luck continued. They checked out of the hotel and were slated to charter to Florida following the game for their next contest in Orlando on Monday. ... With Stoudemire sidelined, veteran Tom Gugliotta made his first start of the season. The Suns also activated C Cezary Trybanski who had been sidelined with back spasms. ... The Nets, for the second straight night, invited fans from the upper level to move down to more expensive seats as a reward for braving the snowstorm.
